<font color="#FF0000">WHAT MUST WE LEARN</font><br>
<tt>Wed Jan 14  5:40:58 US/Eastern 1998
</tt><p>
I hear the voice of complaint by the Vet.<br>
The voice of indignation at being spit at<br>
or looked at as a second class citizen for<br>
doing your part, doing what you thought/<br>
think is right. <br><br>
And now the screw has turned. Welcome<br>
home Vets! But where is the voice of<br>
those who spoke against the war. Why is<br>
it so silent here? Why is it so silent<br>
across America. When was the last time<br>
you heard someone say, oh yeah! I was<br>
against the war. <br><br>
I tried pot, but I didn't inhale... I was<br>
against the war, but I didn't protest...<br>
Same S??? different day.<br><br>
We treat the war like a football game.<br>
One side wins, one side looses. Why<br>
can't we see two sides each with some<br>
right and some wrong.  Why do the<br>
mothers of American who tried to save<br>
their children now have to bow their<br>
heads and remain silent about taking<br>
stands they once were proud of? Why do<br>
we not honor those who fought to save<br>
lives at home, who fought to protect Vet<br>
and Viet alike. <br><br>
We are a society that has a hard time<br>
with diversity. I see on this site people<br>
talking about Charlie, who all fought<br>
high on dope. B.S. They had dopers, so<br>
did we. They had great fighters, so did<br>
we. There Vets cried when friends died,<br>
heros who pulled comrades from under<br>
whithering fire as did we. They had<br>
parents who cried at their deaths, as did<br>
we. They are people, Vets are people and<br>
anti-war protesters are as well. So long<br>
as we make the same mistakes of<br>
objectifying people, boxing and<br>
classifying people, and ignoring the<br>
difference and subtleties in people we<br>
are condemned to making the same<br>
mistakes over and over. <br><br>

<p><code>-- jproujan@k12s.phast.umass.edu  (Jed PRoujansky) </code><p>


